)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intrauterine infection","Physiological jaundice","Red cell haemolysis","Blood group incompatibility","Breast milk jaundice"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEarly onset jaundice with elevated conjugated bilirubin indicates hepatic dysfunction or biliary obstruction. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntrauterine infections\u003C/strong\u003E commonly cause direct liver damage leading to conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia in neonates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysiological jaundice\u003C/strong\u003E typically appears after 24 hours and causes unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed cell haemolysis\u003C/strong\u003E causes increased bilirubin production resulting in unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood group incompatibility\u003C/strong\u003E leads to haemolysis and therefore unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreast milk jaundice\u003C/strong\u003E appears after 3-5 days of life and causes unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia indicates impaired hepatic processing or biliary excretion, rather than increased bilirubin production from red cell breakdown.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia in the first 24 hours of life suggests hepatic dysfunction or biliary obstruction.","Intrauterine infections (particularly cytomegalovirus, toxoplasmosis, and rubella) can cause direct liver damage leading to early conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia.","Conditions causing increased red cell breakdown result in unconjugated rather than 